[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] Polling is the process where the computer or controlling device waits for an external device to check for its readiness or state, often with low-level hardware.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] For example, when a printer is connected via a parallel port, the computer waits until the printer has received the next character.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] These processes can be as minute as only reading one bit.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] This is sometimes used synonymously with 'busy-wait' polling.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] In this situation, when an I/O operation is required, the computer does nothing other than check the status of the I/O device until it is ready, at which point the device is accessed.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] In other words, the computer waits until the device is ready.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] Polling also refers to the situation where a device is repeatedly checked for readiness, and if it is not, the computer returns to a different task.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] Although not as wasteful of CPU cycles as busy waiting, this is generally not as efficient as the alternative to polling, interrupt-driven I/O.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] In a simple single-purpose system, even busy-wait is perfectly appropriate if no action is possible until the I/O access, but more often than not this was traditionally a consequence of simple hardware or non-multitasking operating systems.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] Polling is often intimately involved with very low-level hardware.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] For example, polling a parallel printer port to check whether it is ready for another character involves examining as little as one bit of a byte.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] That bit represents, at the time of reading, whether a single wire in the printer cable is at low or high voltage.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] The I/O instruction that reads this byte directly transfers the voltage state of eight real world wires to the eight circuits (flip flops) that make up one byte of a CPU register.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] Polling has the disadvantage that if there are too many devices to check, the time required to poll them can exceed the time available to service the I/O device.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] When clear, the host writes the command into the command register.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] If the host is sending output, it sets the write bit and writes a byte into the data-out register.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] If the host is receiving input, it reads the controller-written data from the data-in register, and sets the read bit to 0 as the next command.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] The host sets the command-ready bit to 1.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] The controller reads the command register.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] If the write bit inside is set, it reads from the data-out register and performs the necessary I/O operations on the device.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] If the read bit is set, data from the device is loaded into the data-in register for the host to read.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] Once the operations are over, the controller clears the command-ready bit, clears the error bit to show the operation was successful, and clears the busy bit.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] A **polling cycle** is the time in which each element is monitored once.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] The optimal polling cycle will vary according to several factors, including the desired speed of response and the overhead (e.g., processor time and bandwidth) of the polling.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] In **roll call polling**, the polling device or process queries each element on a list in a fixed sequence.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] Because it waits for a response from each element, a timing mechanism is necessary to prevent lock-ups caused by non-responding elements.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] Roll call polling can be inefficient if the overhead for the polling messages is high, there are numerous elements to be polled in each polling cycle and only a few elements are active.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] In *hub polling*, also referred to as token polling, each element polls the next element in some fixed sequence.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] This continues until the first element is reached, at which time the polling cycle starts all over again.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] Polling can be employed in various computing contexts in order to control the execution or transmission sequence of the elements involved.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] For example, in multitasking operating systems, polling can be used to allocate processor time and other resources to the various competing processes.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] In networks, polling is used to determine which nodes want to access the network.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] It is also used by routing protocols to retrieve routing information, as is the case with EGP (exterior gateway protocol).
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] An alternative to polling is the use of interrupts, which are signals generated by devices or processes to indicate that they need attention, want to communicate, etc.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] Although polling can be very simple, in many situations (e.g., multitasking operating systems) it is more efficient to use interrupts because it can reduce processor spinnning and/or bandwidth consumption.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] Sometimes a single interrupt will be shared with multiple devices.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] When such an interrupt is raised, the interrupt service routine will poll the devices sharing the interrupt to determine which needs servicing.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] Vectored interrupts are a more efficient alternative which dispatches each device directly to its own private interrupt service routine.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] A **poll message** is a control-acknowledgment message.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] All terminals listen to the outgoing line, but only the terminal that is polled replies by sending any information that it has ready for transmission on the incoming line.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] In star networks, which, in its simplest form, consists of one central switch, hub, or computer that acts as a conduit to transmit messages, polling is not required to avoid chaos on the lines, but it is often used to allow the master to acquire input in an orderly fashion.
[src:periodic-background-sync/polling-computer-science] These poll messages differ from those of the multidrop lines case because there are no site addresses needed, and each terminal only receives those polls that are directed to it.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:periodic-background-sync/scheduling-computing] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
[src:periodic-background-sync/web-periodic-background-synchronization-api] The **Web Periodic Background Synchronization API** provides a way to register tasks to be run in a service worker at periodic intervals with network connectivity.
[src:periodic-background-sync/web-periodic-background-synchronization-api] The Periodic Background Sync API allows web applications to alert their service worker to make any updates, at a periodic time interval.
[src:periodic-background-sync/web-periodic-background-synchronization-api] Uses may include fetching latest content whilst a device is connected to Wi-Fi, or allowing background updates to an application.
[src:periodic-background-sync/web-periodic-background-synchronization-api] The minimum time interval is set when the API is invoked; however the user agent might also take into account other factors which affect when the service worker receives the event.
[src:periodic-background-sync/web-periodic-background-synchronization-api] For instance previous website engagement, or connection to a known network.
[src:periodic-background-sync/web-periodic-background-synchronization-api] The `PeriodicSyncManager` interface is available through `ServiceWorkerRegistration.periodicSync`.
[src:periodic-background-sync/web-periodic-background-synchronization-api] A unique tag identifier is set to 'name' the sync event, which can then be listened for within the `ServiceWorker` script.
[src:periodic-background-sync/web-periodic-background-synchronization-api] Once the event is received you can then run any functionality available, such as updating caches or fetching new resources.
[src:periodic-background-sync/web-periodic-background-synchronization-api] As this API relies on service workers, functionality provided by this API is only available in a secure context.
[src:periodic-background-sync/web-periodic-background-synchronization-api] Registers tasks to be run in a service worker at periodic intervals with network connectivity.
[src:periodic-background-sync/web-periodic-background-synchronization-api] Represents a synchronization event, sent to the global scope of a ServiceWorker.
[src:periodic-background-sync/web-periodic-background-synchronization-api] It provides a way to run tasks in the service worker with network connectivity.
[src:periodic-background-sync/web-periodic-background-synchronization-api] The following additions to the Service Worker API are specified in the Periodic Background Sync specification to provide an entry point for using Periodic Background Sync.
[src:periodic-background-sync/web-periodic-background-synchronization-api] Returns a reference to the `PeriodicSyncManager` interface for registering tasks to run at specific intervals.
[src:periodic-background-sync/web-periodic-background-synchronization-api] Occurs at periodic intervals, which were specified when registering a `PeriodicSyncManager`.
